Burden of tuberculosis in Serbia.

Gledovic Z(1), Vlajinac H, Pekmezovic T, Grujicic-Sipetic S, Grgurevic A, Pesut 
D.

Author information:
(1)Institute of Epidemiology, School of Medicine, University of Belgrade, 
Visegrdska 26A, Belgrade 11000, Serbia. gledovic@sezampro.yu

The objective of this study is to estimate the burden of tuberculosis (TB) in 
Serbia in the period 1992-2002 based on incidence, mortality, and disability 
adjusted life years (DALY). The average age-adjusted TB incidence rate in the 
period 1992-2002 was 36.7/100,000 in males and 21.4/100,000 in females. During 
the period observed, TB incidence levelled of after a long period of decreasing 
trend during the preceding several decades. The incidence showed slightly 
increasing tendency in males and decreasing one in females. The average 
age-adjusted mortality rate was 4.1/100,000 in males and 1.3/100,000 in females. 
Mortality rates significantly decreased in both males (P = .0001) and females (P 
= .0001). The burden of TB (DALY) was 0.70/1000 for males and 0.26/1000 for 
females. DALY rates significantly decreased in both males (P = .009) and females 
(P = .008). TB incidence and mortality as well as DALY rates increased with 
aging.

